===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|ic}} – two men back to back. Originally meaning “back”; the character {{och-l|背}} refers to the original word.

Compare [[化]], [[比]], [[卬]], and [[尼]].

===Etymology===
From {{inh-lite|zh|sit-pro|*bə(q)||to carry (on back), shoulder}}.

The sense of {{m-g|north}} is derived from {{m-g|back (of body)}}: {{m-g|back}} → {{m-g|to turn the back to; to retreat}} → {{m-g|north}}.

The ancient Chinese value the southern direction and houses are traditionally oriented along a north–south axis, as evident in the ''[[fengshui]]'' theory and in the orientation of buildings in Chinese Neolithic sites. '''North''' is the direction the '''back''' is oriented to when the person is facing south.

Compare the graphical origin of {{och-l|南|gloss=south}} ({{zh-ref|Sagart, 1988}}).

Note the irregular Mandarin reflex (''běi'') from Middle Chinese (unlike the Cantonese reflex, whose form is regular). Expected is ''bo'' (no tone specified because Mandarin reflex tone is unpredictable for Middle Chinese checked syllables), which is nevertheless noted as a literary variant below (namely, ''bò'').

